Misanthropy I can bear - but anti-feline prejudice is different
The cat is man's master, and nobody should challenge its supremacy
Superior: cats expect to be waited on, and invariably get what they deserve Photo: ALAMY	By Michael Deacon
4:52PM GMT 11 Jan 2014
Follow Comments
This week I learnt a disturbing fact about Walt Disney. At an awards dinner in Hollywood, Meryl Streep gave a speech in which she condemned him for his various prejudices. He didn’t like women, he didn’t like Jews, and in fact he probably didn’t much like people in general. None of that shook me; I’d heard it countless times before. But one charge she made was news to me. And when I heard it, I reeled. Walt Disney, Meryl announced grimly, didn’t like cats. Well, really. I mean to say. I’m sorry, Walt, I know you’ve been dead for nearly 50 years and are thus in a less-than- ideal position to answer back. But if what the great Meryl says is true, I’m afraid you and I have had it. The misanthropy I was prepared to put up with. You’re an artist. You hate people. That’s what artists do. Dali, Larkin, Lawrence, Waugh, TS Eliot. Seething misanthropes the lot, say the biographers. For all I know, PG Wodehouse flung darts at photos of nuns and Dr Seuss boiled with a secret loathing for girl guides. None of my business either way, and it would make me think no less of their work even if they did. Anti-feline prejudice, though, is another matter. It has no place in our society. And it must be combated with the utmost vigour wherever it rears its appalling head. Related Articles
