Pet subjects: why is my cat's mood so changeable?
16 Dec 2013
Simon Hoggart
06 Jan 2014
For, as the ancient Egyptians could tell you (do stop and ask them if you happen to see any around), the cat is the foremost of all Earth’s creatures. It sits at the very top of the food chain. And no mere man has the right to challenge it. The cat, after all, is man’s master. Of course it is. Look at the relationship between them. The human “owner” spends his or her hard-earned money providing the cat with food, warmth, shelter, bedding, playthings and veterinary care. And what does the cat give in return? At most, if the human is lucky and the cat is in generous mood, the privilege of stroking its back. Now, imagine an alien were to observe this relationship. Which of these two beings — the cat or the human — would the alien take to be the master? He would take it to be the cat, with the human its pathetically ingratiating servant. And the alien would be right. It is often contended that the cat is a less intelligent creature than, say, the dog, on the grounds that you can’t teach the cat tricks. What an absurd argument. The cat’s unbiddability is proof of its intelligence. Put it this way: say I threw a stick, then turned to you and shouted: “Fetch!” Would you fetch the stick? Of course you wouldn’t. You’d look at me as if I’d gone mad, then ignore me. Exactly as a cat would. A cat recognises stick-fetching for the futile charade it is, and considers it, quite properly, beneath its dignity. Only a dog, poor mindless thing, would be so servile as to fetch the stick. But perhaps I misunderstand Mr Disney’s animus. His hatred of cats may not necessarily have stemmed from a feeling of superiority on his part. Rather, it may have stemmed from a feeling of inferiority. At heart he may simply have feared cats, the way employees fear their bosses. In which case, I believe he deserves our compassion, and I appeal to Miss Streep to show mercy. ...
Watching Prime Minister’s Questions felt strange this week. This is because previously I’d always watched it sitting beside Simon Hoggart, The Guardian’s brilliant sketchwriter. It just wasn’t the same without his muttered asides. He had a particular curmudgeonly relish for planted questions from obsequious Tory backbenchers. (“Well, that was a brain-teaser.”) Every day he sat in the same seat: number 77, at a corner of the press gallery that afforded him the perfect vantage point from which to monitor the movements of David Cameron’s mysterious wandering bald spot. No one sat in seat 77 this week, even when the gallery was at its busiest. West Ham United honoured their greatest player, Bobby Moore, by retiring his shirt number. I propose that parliamentary staff retire seat 77. Personal View
